<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0132">
<l>peyarun toḻilum pirintoruṅ kicaippa</l>
<l>vēṟṟumai yurupu nilaipeṟu vaḻiyun</l>
<l>tōṟṟam vēṇṭāt tokutik kaṇṇu</l>
<l>moṭṭutaṟ koḻukiya vaḻakkoṭu civaṇic</l>
<l>coṟcitar maruṅkiṉ vaḻivantu viḷaṅkā</l>
<l>tiṭainiṉ ṟiyaluñ cāriyai yiyaṟkai</l>
<l>yuṭaimaiyu miṉmaiyu moṭuvayi ṉokkum</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>When a noun is followed by a verb<note place="foot">E.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">viḷa-v-iṉ-ai-k-kuṟaittāṉ ; pu-v-iṉ-oṭu</foreign>
          or <foreign xml:lang="ta">pū-v-oṭu.</foreign> The examples quoted Iḷam. show, first, that
          the <foreign xml:lang="ta">viṉai</foreign> meant here is either finite verb or participal noun (<foreign xml:lang="ta">viḷaviṉaikkuṟaittavaṉ</foreign> is quoted) and, second, that the order meant is Noun + Verb.</note></l>
<l>it is the nature of the empty morph to be inserted,</l>
<l>according to the rules of sandhi, between the base</l>
<l>and the case-marker, or after the base</l>
<l>when the case-marker is dropped,</l>
<l>though when the two words are pronounced separately,</l>
<l>the empty-morph disappears.</l>
<l>Between the base and the marker - <foreign xml:lang="ta">oṭu,</foreign></l>
<l>it both appears and disappears.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
